{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491254","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491254"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:39:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:39:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"892"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"892","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/892"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.01,0.11,0.6,0.27]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"892"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"28935"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"892","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/892"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"892"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"15130"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"404"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1251"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1343"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6989"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16129"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"28935","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/28935"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 65-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department following a fall where she tripped on the edge of a carpet. She denies any preceding symptoms. On examination, her left leg is shortened and externally rotated. Her peripheral pulses are strong and her legs are warm to touch. There is no obvious haematoma. She is tender over the left lateral thigh but not in the pelvis. A pelvis X-ray shows a fracture through the junction of the head and neck of femur with partial displacement.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate definitive management approach?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Conservative management","Pelvic binder","Closed reduction, application of plaster","Hemiarthroplasty","Dynamic hip screws"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has an unstable (ie, displaced) femoral neck fracture. Femoral neck fractures are classified based on Garden classification, which is given below:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIncomplete fracture = Garden I\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EComplete non-displaced fracture = Garden II\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EComplete partially displaced fracture = Garden III\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EComplete fully displaced fracture = Garden IV\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient most likely has a Garden III femoral fracture. Femoral neck fracture presents with groin pain and externally rotated leg on examination. It is seen more commonly in elderly patients due to age-related weakening of the bones. It may be seen in young patients after major trauma (eg, motor vehicle accidents). Patients with a displaced femoral fracture are at high risk of several complications (eg, avascular necrosis, malunion, infection, thromboembolism). The diagnosis is generally confirmed with X-rays. The management plan depends on the patient\u0027s age and whether the fracture is displaced or non-displaced.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStable and non-displaced fractures (ie, Garden I \u0026amp; II) in the elderly are generally managed with internal fixation but may be treated conservatively in rare circumstances.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnstable and displaced fractures (ie, Garden III \u0026amp; IV) in the elderly may be treated with \u003Cstrong\u003Ehemiarthroplasty\u003C/strong\u003E or total hip replacement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESince this patient has a displaced femoral neck fracture, \u003Cstrong\u003Ehemiarthroplasty\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate treatment option among the answer choices. Whilst not given as an option, a total hip arthroplasty could be considered as the treatment plan. The choice between total hip and hemiarthroplasty is controversial.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EConservative management or internal fixation are treatment options for stable and non-displaced femoral neck fractures (Garden I \u0026amp; II) in the elderly. They may be considered in displaced fractures in young patients. Internal fixation in displaced fractures in the elderly are associated with an increased risk of reoperation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA pelvic binder is recommended for pelvic fracture. A pelvic binder would compress the pelvic bone in order to prevent or control bleeding after the fracture. This patient does not need a pelvic binder considering his non-tender pelvis and X-ray findings unremarkable for pelvic fracture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EClosed reduction with application of plaster was the management of femoral fractures in the past. However, it was associated with a high risk of non-union, pressure sores, respiratory complications. With the advent of newer treatments, these risks have been significantly improved.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Some form of arthroplasty is required for unstable femoral neck fractures."],"references":["Griffiths R, Alper J, Beckingsale A, Goldhill D, Heyburn G, Holloway J et al. Management of proximal femoral fractures 2011. Anaesthesia. 2011;67(1):85-98.","Jain A, Sandhu H, Dhillon M. Femoral neck fractures. Indian Journal of Orthopaedics. 2008;42(1):1."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"15130"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"892"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"15130","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/15130"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2022-10-06T13:37:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-27T10:44:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"892"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"28935"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"404","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/404"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Neck of femur fracture","synonyms":["Fractured neck of femur","Fractured NOF","NOFF"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-05-19T22:40:05+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-11T13:25:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"2"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"contribu